          /AUTOMATED METADATA EXTRACTION FROM LEGAL TEXTS/

           CONTEXT

The premise for the collaboration proposal described herein is a series of
meeting between the Service Central de Législation (SCL) and the Software
Verification and Validation Laboratory (SVV) at SnT. These meetings were
aimed at exploring avenues to provide automated support to SCL in the
digitization of Luxembourg’s legal corpora. SVV is already engaged with
SCL in the process of transforming Luxembourgish legal codes into XML
format through Natural Language Processing (NLP). To further this existing
collaboration beyond the structural aspects of legal texts and to better
account for semantic considerations, SVV and SCL considered and discussed
several research directions. An important conclusion that emerged from this
endeavour is that semantic metadata extraction would be a key enabler and
prerequisite for two high-priority areas: (1) smart search in legal texts
and (2) transitioning from legal texts described in natural language
(French) to rule-based legislation, that is legislation expressed as
logical rules.
In light of the above conclusion, semantic metadata extraction was deemed
to be an essential starting point for research. The remainder of this
proposal provides a concrete vision of how SVV and SCL can engage in a
collaborative R&D partnership to address this topic.

           INTRODUCTION

 Searching the law for specific information is a pervasive challenge in
public administration and e-Governance. When looking for legal information,
stakeholders (including citizens, administration personnel, legal experts,
and IT departments in charge of developing public administration systems)
may need to narrow the interpretation of the law to specific concerns, for
example, the actions to be taken if a given condition is met, or the steps
to follow when a given administrative process is to be enacted.
In Luxembourg, the existing LegiLux portal is an important step towards
supporting search. Nevertheless, the portal does not yet support advanced
semantic search, notably searching based on conditions and administrative
processes, as described above. In a similar vein, the existing
“guichet.lu[2]” service is geared towards providing
a /static/ guidance about typical cases that citizens may encounter.
However, the current service does not provide the flexibility for citizens
to obtain /dynamic /guidance, tailored to the specific circumstances and
considerations that apply to them.
For this, we propose to develop semi-automated means for extracting
semantic information from legal texts. This information will be stored as
semantic metadata that can be further analysed and combined for supporting
smart querying capabilities and for assisting analysts in extracting the
underlying rules and business processes from natural-language legal texts.
The benefits from this research project for SCL will be twofold. First, the
project outcomes will provide significant automated assistance for
analysing and annotating legal texts, thus reducing costs associated with a
fully manual annotation and in turn increasing the potential to cover a
much wider set of laws with smart search capabilities. Second, this
research will contribute to lowering the gap between the law and the
systems that are subject to legal compliance. In particular, the project
outcomes will enable more systematic traceability between legal texts and
IT systems, which is essential for maintaining the compliance of IT systems
as legal texts are amended over time.

           RESEARCH PRIORITIES

 From our discussions with SCL, we identify the following research
priorities: (1) (semi-)automated extraction of semantic metadata from legal
texts, (2) development of a query language for smart search based on the
extracted metadata, and (3) investigation of how the extracted metadata can
be leveraged for deriving rules and business processes.
/CONCEPTUAL SPECIFICATION OF METADATA: /Maintaining metadata for
heterogeneous web resources (text, pictures, movies) is a key promise of
Internet 2.0, also known as the semantic web. Such metadata provides, among
other things, the flexibility to consider the resources in smart search. An
important question to tackle with respect to metadata is its
representation. To this end, it is necessary to investigate existing
approaches for metadata specification, and to determine whether any of
these approaches provide a suitable basis for customisation in the context
of SCL.
/METADATA EXTRACTION: /Once the metadata items of interest have been
conceptually defined in a suitable representation, one needs to develop
strategies and rules for automated extraction of these items. A key
consideration in developing such strategies and rules is that metadata
often has a/ hierarchical /nature, meaning that simpler metadata items
may be combined in order to produce more sophisticated metadata items.
Since the extraction of semantic metadata is largely heuristic, one can
never be entirely sure whether automatically-extracted metadata is fully
accurate and complete. It is therefore important to intertwine automation
with an iterative human-in-the-loop process in order to incrementally
verify and improve the results of automation.
/DERIVATION OF LEGAL RULES AND BUSINESS PROCESSES: /Moving from
natural-language legal texts to rule-based legislation necessarily requires
the construction of legal rules and business processes that are aligned
with the existing texts. An important research priority is therefore to
investigate how the metadata acquisition process can help in building a key
understanding of the underlying legal provisions. Appropriate guidance and
automated assistance should further be developed to facilitate the
transition from this (informal) understanding to rigorous models of legal
rules and business processes.



